#!/usr/bin/env python3
"""Generate a container-local settings JSON that wraps each hook command in
/usr/local/bin/exec-hook, so cross-arch host binaries no-op silently instead
of spamming "Exec format error" on every invocation.

WHY THIS EXISTS

Operators bind-mount ~/.claude into the container, including
~/.claude/settings.json with its `hooks.<event>.[*].hooks[*].command`
entries. When the host is macOS (or any non-Linux platform), those
commands often point at host-native binaries — devbar's
telemetry-hook, etc. — that Linux's exec() bounces with "Exec format
error". Claude Code logs the failure on every hook event; the noise
buries real diagnostics.

PR #135 shipped /usr/local/bin/exec-hook, a magic-byte sniffer that
exec's ELF / shebang transparently and silently no-ops on Mach-O /
unknown. The shim is opt-in: the operator has to MANUALLY edit each
hook command in their settings.json to wrap it as
  "command": "exec-hook /Users/me/.devbar/bin/telemetry-hook"
On a Mac host where settings.json is bind-mounted in, that edit is
load-bearing on the HOST and surprises the host install.

This helper produces a container-local copy of settings.json with
every hook command wrapped, so the operator doesn't have to mutate
the host file. It is invoked by container/entrypoint.sh when
CLAUDE_CONTAINER_REWRITE_HOOKS=1 is set. The generated file lives at
$OUTPUT_PATH (default /tmp/claude-shim/settings.json, uid 1000
writable). The entrypoint then launches claude with
`--settings $OUTPUT_PATH` so Claude Code merges the rewritten hooks
on top of its normal user/project/local cascade.

WHY MCP SERVERS ARE NOT HANDLED HERE

PR #145 tried to merge `mcpServers` into this shim file. v21 workbot
validation surfaced that Claude Code v2.1.141 does NOT read MCP server
definitions from settings.json files at any tier — it loads them from
`~/.claude.json` via a separate code path that is gated on the `user`
tier being in `--setting-sources`. Since the entrypoint passes
`--setting-sources project,local` (to drop the bare host hooks), the
`.claude.json` MCP path is suppressed and Claude Code reports "No MCP
servers configured" regardless of what's in the shim settings.json.

The fix lives in a sibling helper `generate-project-mcp-json` which
writes a `.mcp.json` file into the project dir (project tier IS in
`--setting-sources project,local`). This script no longer touches
mcpServers at all.

PATTERN FILTERING (--shim-patterns / CLAUDE_SHIM_PATTERNS)

By default this helper wraps EVERY hook command it finds. Operators
who only want a NARROW subset wrapped (e.g. just corp telemetry hooks
under `/Users/*/.devbar/bin/*`) can pass `--shim-patterns` (or set
`CLAUDE_SHIM_PATTERNS` in the env) to a colon-separated list of glob
patterns. When the flag/env is set to a non-empty value, ONLY commands
whose first token (the binary path) matches at least one pattern are
wrapped; the rest pass through verbatim.

Matching is done with `fnmatch.fnmatchcase` against the FIRST
whitespace-separated token of the command (post-`lstrip`). Globs use
the standard shell wildcards: `*` (any chars except `/` is NOT a
special case — `fnmatch` treats `*` as any chars, so a pattern like
`/Users/*/bin/*` will match `/Users/me/bin/foo` AND `/Users/me/sub/bin/foo`
— mirror what an operator typing the glob into a shell would expect).

Separator is `:` (parallel to `PATH`). Paths containing `:` are
extraordinarily rare on real systems; if you have one, use a more
specific pattern that doesn't depend on the colon.

Default behavior preserved: when the flag/env is unset OR an empty
string, EVERY hook command is wrapped — same as pre-PR-#147 behavior.
This is the operator-safe default: on a non-Linux host with cross-arch
hooks, wrap-everything is the right call because the shim is
transparent on ELF / shebang, no-op on Mach-O, so the only "cost" of
over-wrapping is one extra exec() hop per hook fire.

NON-GOALS

- We do NOT inspect the target binary's magic bytes here. The shim
  itself does that at hook-fire time, per-target. This helper just
  wraps EVERY hook command unconditionally (or every command matching
  the operator's patterns). That's safe: the shim is transparent for
  ELF and shebang targets (exec passthrough); the only behaviour
  change for native-Linux hooks is one extra exec() hop per fire,
  which is negligible.
- We do NOT mutate the host's settings.json. The output is a
  container-local file at a deterministic path under /tmp.
- We do NOT support negative patterns yet. If you need an
  "everything except X" shape, file an issue and we'll add a
  `!pattern` syntax.

INPUT FORMAT

~/.claude/settings.json schema (per Claude Code docs):
  {
    "hooks": {
      "<event>": [
        {
          "matcher": "...",
          "hooks": [
            { "type": "command", "command": "/path/to/hook [args]" },
            ...
          ]
        },
        ...
      ],
      ...
    },
    "<other-top-level-keys>": ...
  }

This script rewrites:
  - `hooks.<event>.[*].hooks[*].command`
All other top-level keys are passed through unchanged.

OUTPUT FORMAT

Same settings.json schema with each hook command rewritten:
  "command": "/usr/local/bin/exec-hook <original-command-verbatim>"

The original command may already start with "exec-hook " (the
operator pre-wrapped on the host). In that case we don't double-wrap.

EXIT CODES

  0  output written successfully, or input lacks any hooks
     (graceful no-op)
  1  unexpected error parsing input / writing output

The script is fail-safe: on parse error / missing input, it logs to
stderr and exits 0 so the entrypoint can keep going. Bad-input cases
shouldn't break the container.
"""

from __future__ import annotations

import argparse
import fnmatch
import json
import os
import sys
from pathlib import Path

EXEC_HOOK_PATH = "/usr/local/bin/exec-hook"


def parse_patterns(raw: str | None) -> list[str]:
    """Split a colon-separated pattern list into a clean list of globs.

    Empty / None input returns []. Empty tokens (e.g. trailing colon)
    are dropped so `"foo:"` yields `["foo"]` not `["foo", ""]`. Tokens
    are NOT stripped of internal whitespace — operator-supplied globs
    are taken verbatim.

    Returns [] to signal "no filter, wrap everything" (the default).
    """
    if not raw:
        return []
    return [p for p in raw.split(":") if p]


def command_first_token(cmd: str) -> str:
    """Return the first whitespace-separated token of `cmd` after
    lstrip(). This is the natural target for pattern matching — the
    binary the hook actually invokes. Returns "" for empty / all-space
    input.

    We intentionally do NOT shlex-parse here: hook commands often
    contain shell pipes / env-var expansions / quoting that shlex
    would mishandle (or worse, "succeed" with wrong tokenization).
    Whitespace-split on the head is good enough for matching binary
    paths, which is the only thing patterns are aimed at.
    """
    stripped = cmd.lstrip() if cmd else ""
    if not stripped:
        return ""
    # Split on the first run of whitespace; head is the binary.
    return stripped.split(None, 1)[0]


def command_matches_patterns(cmd: str, patterns: list[str]) -> bool:
    """True iff `cmd`'s first token matches at least one glob in
    `patterns`. Empty `patterns` returns True (wrap-everything default).

    Matching uses `fnmatch.fnmatchcase` so patterns are case-sensitive
    on all platforms (we don't want a pattern like `/Users/*/bin/*` to
    silently accept a different case on a case-insensitive host volume
    — operators specify their paths as-is).
    """
    if not patterns:
        return True
    head = command_first_token(cmd)
    if not head:
        return False
    return any(fnmatch.fnmatchcase(head, p) for p in patterns)


def wrap_command(cmd: str, patterns: list[str] | None = None) -> str:
    """Prefix `cmd` with `exec-hook ` unless already wrapped or filtered
    out by the operator's pattern list.

    `cmd` is the raw "command" string from settings.json — typically a
    shell-ready string like "/path/to/hook arg1 arg2". We DON'T tokenise
    + re-quote it because hook commands frequently rely on shell features
    (pipes, env-var expansion, redirection); naive shlex would break
    those. Instead we just prefix the literal exec-hook path.

    Edge cases handled:
      - command already starts with "exec-hook " or "/usr/local/bin/exec-hook ":
        return verbatim (no double-wrap).
      - command starts with whitespace: stripped before prefix check, but
        original whitespace preserved in the output (so funky operator
        whitespace round-trips).
      - command is empty: returned as-is (Claude Code will reject it
        on its own; not our problem to validate).
      - `patterns` is None or [] → wrap unconditionally (default).
      - `patterns` non-empty → wrap only if the command's first token
        matches at least one pattern; otherwise pass through unchanged.
    """
    if not cmd:
        return cmd
    stripped = cmd.lstrip()
    # Already wrapped — don't double-prefix.
    if stripped.startswith("exec-hook ") or stripped.startswith(f"{EXEC_HOOK_PATH} "):
        return cmd
    # Bare "exec-hook" or bare exec-hook path with no args is a usage
    # error in settings.json but pass it through unchanged rather than
    # rewriting; the shim will print its usage banner on stderr at
    # fire time and exit 2, which is the operator-visible signal we want.
    if stripped == "exec-hook" or stripped == EXEC_HOOK_PATH:
        return cmd
    # Operator-supplied pattern filter — pass through if no match.
    if patterns and not command_matches_patterns(cmd, patterns):
        return cmd
    return f"{EXEC_HOOK_PATH} {cmd}"


def rewrite_hooks(settings: dict, patterns: list[str] | None = None) -> dict:
    """Walk settings["hooks"] and wrap every nested command. Returns a
    new dict; the input is not mutated.

    Tolerates missing / malformed shapes by leaving them alone — Claude
    Code's own validator will complain about the original shape and we
    don't want to silently "fix" something we don't understand."""
    out = dict(settings)  # shallow copy is fine, we deep-copy the hooks tree
    hooks = settings.get("hooks")
    if not isinstance(hooks, dict):
        return out
    new_hooks: dict = {}
    for event, entries in hooks.items():
        if not isinstance(entries, list):
            new_hooks[event] = entries
            continue
        new_entries = []
        for entry in entries:
            if not isinstance(entry, dict):
                new_entries.append(entry)
                continue
            new_entry = dict(entry)
            inner = entry.get("hooks")
            if isinstance(inner, list):
                new_inner = []
                for hook in inner:
                    if not isinstance(hook, dict):
                        new_inner.append(hook)
                        continue
                    new_hook = dict(hook)
                    cmd = hook.get("command")
                    if isinstance(cmd, str):
                        new_hook["command"] = wrap_command(cmd, patterns)
                    new_inner.append(new_hook)
                new_entry["hooks"] = new_inner
            new_entries.append(new_entry)
        new_hooks[event] = new_entries
    out["hooks"] = new_hooks
    return out


def main(argv: list[str]) -> int:
    p = argparse.ArgumentParser(
        description="Generate a container-local settings JSON with every "
                    "hook command wrapped in /usr/local/bin/exec-hook.",
    )
    p.add_argument(
        "--input", "-i",
        default=os.environ.get("CLAUDE_SHIM_INPUT", "/home/hndrewaall/.claude/settings.json"),
        help="Path to the source settings.json (default: ~/.claude/settings.json).",
    )
    p.add_argument(
        "--output", "-o",
        default=os.environ.get("CLAUDE_SHIM_OUTPUT", "/tmp/claude-shim/settings.json"),
        help="Path to write the rewritten settings.json to. Created with "
             "0600 perms; parent dir created if missing.",
    )
    p.add_argument(
        "--shim-patterns",
        default=os.environ.get("CLAUDE_SHIM_PATTERNS", ""),
        help="Colon-separated list of glob patterns. When non-empty, "
             "only hook commands whose first token (the binary path) "
             "matches at least one pattern are wrapped with exec-hook; "
             "non-matching commands pass through verbatim. Empty / unset "
             "= wrap every command (default, backward-compatible). "
             "Falls back to CLAUDE_SHIM_PATTERNS env var if the flag "
             "isn't given. Example: "
             "'/Users/*/.devbar/bin/*:/Users/*/.devbar/pkgs/*/bin/*'.",
    )
    p.add_argument(
        "--quiet", "-q",
        action="store_true",
        help="Suppress stderr 'wrote N hooks' summary on success.",
    )
    args = p.parse_args(argv)
    patterns = parse_patterns(args.shim_patterns)

    in_path = Path(args.input)
    out_path = Path(args.output)

    if not in_path.exists():
        if not args.quiet:
            print(
                f"generate-hooks-shim-settings: input {in_path} does not exist; nothing to rewrite.",
                file=sys.stderr,
            )
        return 0

    try:
        with in_path.open("r", encoding="utf-8") as f:
            settings = json.load(f)
    except Exception as e:
        print(
            f"generate-hooks-shim-settings: failed to parse {in_path}: {e}",
            file=sys.stderr,
        )
        return 0  # fail-safe: don't break the container

    if not isinstance(settings, dict):
        print(
            f"generate-hooks-shim-settings: {in_path} root is not a JSON object; skipping.",
            file=sys.stderr,
        )
        return 0

    rewritten = rewrite_hooks(settings, patterns)

    out_path.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    # Write to a temp file then atomic-rename so a concurrent claude
    # launch never sees a half-written file.
    tmp_path = out_path.with_suffix(out_path.suffix + ".tmp")
    with tmp_path.open("w", encoding="utf-8") as f:
        json.dump(rewritten, f, indent=2, ensure_ascii=False)
        f.write("\n")
    os.chmod(tmp_path, 0o600)
    os.replace(tmp_path, out_path)

    if not args.quiet:
        # Count hooks we touched for the operator's awareness. With
        # pattern filtering, the wrapped count may be < total — surface
        # both so it's obvious when patterns matched 0/N commands.
        n_hooks = 0
        n_wrapped = 0
        hooks = rewritten.get("hooks") or {}
        for entries in hooks.values():
            if not isinstance(entries, list):
                continue
            for entry in entries:
                inner = (entry or {}).get("hooks") or []
                for hook in inner:
                    cmd = (hook or {}).get("command")
                    if isinstance(cmd, str):
                        n_hooks += 1
                        if cmd.lstrip().startswith(f"{EXEC_HOOK_PATH} ") or \
                                cmd.lstrip().startswith("exec-hook "):
                            n_wrapped += 1
        if patterns:
            print(
                f"generate-hooks-shim-settings: wrote {n_hooks} hook(s), "
                f"{n_wrapped} wrapped (patterns={patterns}) -> {out_path}",
                file=sys.stderr,
            )
        else:
            print(
                f"generate-hooks-shim-settings: wrote {n_hooks} hook(s) -> {out_path}",
                file=sys.stderr,
            )

    return 0


if __name__ == "__main__":
    sys.exit(main(sys.argv[1:]))
